 dN/dL $\\propto L^{-2.5\\pm0.3}$ - significantly steeper than\nthe previously derived scaling of $L^{-1.4\\pm0.3}$ for lower luminosity LRNe\n(M$_{V}\\geq-10$). The steeper power law for LRNe at high luminosities is\nconsistent with the massive merger rates predicted by binary population\nsynthesis models. We find that the rates of the brightest LRNe (M$_{r}\\leq-13$\nmag) are consistent with a significant fraction of them being progenitors of\ndouble compact objects (DCOs) that merge within a Hubble time. For ILRTs, we\nderive a volumetric rate of $2.6^{+1.8}_{-1.4}\\times10^{-6}$\nMpc$^{-3}$yr$^{-1}$ for M$_{\\rm{r}}\\leq-13.5$, that scales as dN/dL $\\propto\nL^{-2.5\\pm0.5}$. This rate is $\\approx1-5\\%$ of the local core-collapse\nsupernova rate, and is consistent with theoretical ECSN rate estimates.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 9 Nov 2022 19:00:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-24"}
